Linux Filesystem Directory Structure

Directory           : Means            : Description

/bin                : Binary           : Contains essential system binaries (ls, cp, mv) used by all users.
/boot               : -                : Stores boot files, including the kernel and bootloader configurations.
/dev                : Device           : Contains device files representing hardware components.
/etc                : Config           : System configuration files for services and applications.
/home               : User Data        : User personal directories and data.
/lib                : Libraries        : Shared libraries and kernel modules required by system binaries.
/lost+found         : Recovery         : Used to recover corrupted or lost files after filesystem errors.
/media              : Removable Media  : Mount point for removable media (USB drives, CDs).
/mnt                : Mount            : Temporary mount point for mounting filesystems and devices manually.
/opt                : Optional         : Stores optional and third-party software packages.
/proc               : Process Info     : Virtual filesystem providing information about system processes and kernel parameters.
/root               : Root Home        : Home directory of the root (superuser) account.
/run                : Runtime          : Stores runtime data for system processes since the last boot.
/sbin               : Superuser Binary : Essential system binaries used by the superuser for system administration.
/srv                : Service Data     : Contains data for services like FTP, web, or databases.
/tmp                : Temporary        : Temporary files used by applications, cleared on reboot.
/usr                : User Programs    : User applications, libraries, and documentation.
/var                : Variable Data    : Variable data files such as logs, mail, spool files, and databases.
